There are some times in JIRA where we need to do a sync with all user directories (for example during an upgrade or in studio during tests). It would seem that we should call CrowdDirectoryService.synchroniseDirectory(..., false). However, as documented this throws an exception if the directory is already being synchronized. So you end up with:

{code}
        List<Directory> allDirectories = directoryService.findAllDirectories();
        for (Directory directory : allDirectories)
        {
            Long id = directory.getId();
            if (directory.isActive() && directoryService.isDirectorySynchronisable(id)
                    && !directoryService.isDirectorySynchronising(id))
            {
                try
                {
                    directoryService.synchroniseDirectory(id, false);
                }
                catch (OperationFailedException e)
                {
                    log.error(format("Unable to synchronize directory %s [%s].", directory.getName(), directory.getId()), e);
                }
            }
        }
{code}

We have to catch the exception because just checking directoryService.isDirectorySynchronising(id) does not guarantee that the call to directoryService.synchroniseDirectory(id, false) will not throw an exception because the directory is now synchronizing.

To make this method better to use here is what I think should happen:

* If directoryService.synchroniseDirectory(id, false) is called when a sync is already happening: The method should wait for the current sync to finish and return false. If i am calling this method I really just want a sync to have happened once I return and I really don't care if I trigger it or someone else does. The return value can be used by the caller in a loop if they really really really want to force a sync.
* If directoryService.synchroniseDirectory(id, false) is called when no sync is happening: Do the sync and return true.
* If directoryService.synchroniseDirectory(id, true) is called when a sync is happening: Return immediately and return false. 
* If directoryService.synchroniseDirectory(id, true) is called when a sync is not happening: Return immediately and return true.

All this is possible to implement with a few extensions to the {{DirectoryLockManager}}.

For even more points: As a host app all I really want to do is either make sure all my users are synchronized or to start a synchronization programatically. It would be nice if there was a some simple methods:

* CrowdDirectoryService.synchronizeAndWait(...): Synchronize all the directories waiting for the passed time for the operation to complete.
* CrowdDirectoryService.startSynchronize(queueRequest, ...): Start the directories synchronizing and return immediately.

The synchroniseCache basically does this:

{code}
if (isSynchronising(directoryId))
{
  throw new OperationFailedException("Directory " + directoryId + " is currently synchronising");
}
directorySynchroniser.synchronise((SynchronisableDirectory) remoteDirectory, mode);
{code}

The isSynchronising method is documented to be non-reliable. If is possible, though unlikely, for the isSynchronising to return false and the call to directorySynchroniser.synchronise to actually do nothing. It would be better if the directorySynchroniser.synchronise actually returned a boolean indicating whether or not the call actually started a sync. You could then use this to throw an error if necessary.

